{
  "text": "Lipodystrophy may be partial or total 2 . The patient we describe has partial lipodystrophy, which may be familial (autosomal dominant) or sporadic [CITATION_1] . In the sporadic form, females are more frequently affected than males and subcutaneous fat is progressively lost from the upper body and face. The aetiology of the lipodystrophies is unknown. The partial form has been found in various other disorders, some autoimmune 4\u00b16 . All forms of lipodystrophy are associated with insulin resistance and dyslipidaemia; other common features include hirsutism, acanthosis nigricans, menstrual abnormalities and PCOS 7 . Indeed, primary insulin resistance is now thought to underlie isolated PCOS and associated hyperandrogenism [CITATION_2] .",
  "citation_candidates": [
