  ],
  "bib_entries": {
    "7297623": {
      "title": "Localization of the gene for familial partial lipodystrophy (Dunnigan variety) to chromosome 1q21\u00b122",
      "abstract": "Obesity is strongly implicated in the pathophysiology of insulin resistance, diabetes mellitus and dyslipidemia1\u20133. The mechanisms, however, by which obesity causes these complications are not known. The study of single-gene disorders affecting adipose tissue may elucidate some of the mechanisms involved in these processes. Familial partial lipodystrophy, Dunnigan variety, (FPLD, OMIM 308980) is an autosomal-dominant condition characterized by marked loss of subcutaneous adipose tissue affecting the trunk and extremities but with excess fat deposition in the head and neck areas4\u201314. Affected individuals show an increased preponderance of insulin resistance, diabetes mellitus, dyslipidemia and acanthosis nigricans4\u201314. The genetic basis of FPLD is unknown. We carried out a genome-wide scan with a set of highly polymorphic short tandem-repeats (STR) in individuals from five well-characterized pedigrees and mapped the FPLD locus to chromosome 1q21\u201322. The maximum two-point lod score obtained with a highly polymorphic microsatellite at D1S2624 at \u03b8max=0 was 5.84. Multipoint-linkage analysis yielded a peak lod score of 8.25 between D75305 and D1S1600. There was no evidence for genetic heterogeneity (\u03b1=1) in the pedigrees."
    },
    "32902668": {
      "title": "Insulin resistance in polycystic ovary syndrome: treating a phenotype without a genotype",
      "abstract": "Abstract PCOS women are uniquely insulin resistant. The underlying genetic defect in insulin action is unknown. Obesity aggravates the underlying predisposition to insulin resistance. Diagnostic criteria which focus on menstrual irregularity are more likely to identify insulin resistant women. About 40% of PCOS women display glucose intolerance (either impaired glucose tolerance or type 2 diabetes) in response to an oral glucose challenge. The lack of a clear etiologic mechanism to the syndrome has led to a multitude of symptom-oriented treatments with few therapies improving all aspects of the endocrine syndrome of PCOS. Empirical studies of interventions improving insulin sensitivity in PCOS, either weight loss/diet programs or pharmaceutical agents, have been shown to improve the endocrine abnormalities in the syndrome. These initial results with anti-diabetic agents, though promising, need to be confirmed in larger, randomized studies."
    },
    "40328149": {
      "title": "Renal disease in partial lipodystrophy",
      "abstract": "Five patients, two male and three female, with partial lipodystrophy and renal disease are presented. The lipodystrophy followed a childhood infective illness in at least two patients. Its extent was variable but facial involvement was constant. Other features found apart from renal disease were hirsuties, pigmentation, hepatosplenomegaly, and diabetes mellitus. Hypertension was a constant feature. There was a strong suggestion that renal disease in the three female patients had either started in pregnancy or had been aggravated by it. Renal function varied from normal to chronic renal failure, and one patient required renal transplantation. Proteinuria was a constant finding and the nephrotic syndrome occurred in three patients. Renal histology was obtained in all the patients and showed a glomerulonephritis of variable morphology. Electron microscopy was performed on two of the samples and confirmed the presence of glomerulonephritis and showed an unevenly thickened capillary basement membrane containing electron-dense deposits. It is suggested that the nephropathy in partial lipodystrophy is secondary to some as yet unspecified immunological lesion."
    }
  }
}